Java Methods

1) Methods are block of statements which are used to do specific task. 

2) Methods are generally used to divide a large code into manageable chunks of codes. 

e.g. int sum(int x, int y)
     {
      int z = x + y; 
      return z;
     }
     // int - Return Type / sum - Method Name / int x, int y - Value passed to the method
     
3) Method Declaration:
   
   a) Access/NonAccess Modifier
   b) returnType
   c) MethodName(Parameter List)
   d) {
   e) // Method body or statement block
   f) }
   
   public class Stocks
   {
   
   public void go (int x)
   {
   System.out.println(x);
   }
   
   }
   
4) Method Return Type
-> It may be possible that a method returns a value or doesn't returns any value
-> Return type of a method is nothing but the data type of the value returned by the method.
-> Method return an integer value then return type will be 'int', for flat 'float', for character 'char', for boolean 'boolean'
-> If a method doesn't returns any value then return value then it's return type is 'void'\
-> If a method returns a value then the last statement should be a 'return statement'
-> Any code after return statement is not reachable
-> e.g. 

   public class Stocks
   {
   
   public int go (int x)
   {
   	return x;
   }
   
   }